I base these figures on a Monte Carlo model I built in excel. I assign probabilities to each house race using figures from 538's deluxe model. Then I run trials in which each race has that chance of a democrat winning. However, this treats the outcome of each race as an independent event, when in reality they are all affected by common factors. E. g., a change in the generic ballot will cause the probability of democratic victory to shift across the board for all races. So I need to find a way to make the outcomes correlate with each other, so that a democratic win in one district means a higher chance of a democratic win in all other districts, and vice versa.  I take the probabilities and modify them by a single random number, so that democratic victories are either made more or less probable across the board. Even this is not enough, since changes in the generic ballot will affect "toss-up" races more than safe seats. To solve this, I convert the random number into a likelihood ratio between 1:2.5 and 2.5:1, and feed it into Bayes Theorem (the priors are given by 538's forecasts). Races with probabilities closest to 50% are modified the most, while those closer to 0% or 100% are modified the least. So by simulating each race and altering the chances of democratic victory using a random likelihood ratio and Bayes Theorem, I (hopefully) capture the randomness involved in each race as well as the correlation between the results of all the races. I run the simulation 52 times, and 63% of them result in between 11 and 15 seats being won by democrats, 33% between 16 and 20, etc.

http://editions.lib.umn.edu/smartpolitics/2018/08/13/how-often-do-seats-flip-in-rematches-of-us-house-special-elections/
The 1974, 1980, 1998, and 2008 cycles each hosted four such rematches between special election candidates in November. But how often do these second chances pay off? Smart Politics reviewed the 209 U.S. House special elections conducted from 1968 through 2016 and found that 173 of them were not held simultaneously with a November general election. Of these 173 specials, the nominees in 41 of them squared off again in the subsequent general election. [Note: Smart Politics tallied contests in which the winner of the special faced either the second-place finisher in the special or, if the second-place finisher was a third party or independent candidate who did not run in the general, then another major party nominee who was on the ballot in both elections]. In just six of these 41 rematches was the loser of the special election able to knock the recently elected freshman U.S. Representative out of office, and in just two of the last 29 rematches since 1981.
